    <article class="prose prose-zinc max-w-none dark:prose-invert prose-sm sm:prose-base">
      <p>I was cutting long before I was licensed. Garages, back porches, dorm bathrooms — anywhere I could plug in. I even got fined for it. But I kept at it. When I finally stepped into school, I brought experience, not just curiosity. Still, the state board was its own beast. Here's how to walk in prepared and walk out passed — first try.</p>

      <h2>1. Know What’s On the Test</h2>
      <p>Sanitation. Anatomy. Hair cutting. Chemical services. State law. And that hands-on practical. Know your state’s candidate bulletin front to back. That’s your blueprint.</p>

      <h2>2. Use Focused Study Tools</h2>
      <p>Forget scrolling random tips. Use what’s built for this. At FadeJunkie, we’ve got <strong>flashcards</strong> for the written and an <strong>eBook</strong> that walks you through the practical, step-by-step. Grab both in the <a href="#students">Student section</a>.</p>

      <h2>3. Study in Blocks, Not Marathons</h2>
      <p>Short, focused study sessions (like 25 minutes on, 5 minutes off) work better. Repeat. Test yourself often. Teach it out loud to lock it in.</p>

      <h2>4. Talk to People Who’ve Been There</h2>
      <p>Whether it's your instructor, a friend who passed, or a Reddit group — learn from someone who's seen the test. You’ll get more insight than any study guide can give.</p>

      <h2>5. Handle Test Day Like a Pro</h2>
      <p>Show up early. Stay calm. Follow directions to the letter. It’s not about perfect blends — it’s about sanitation, safety, and being steady under pressure.</p>

